post_text:
Kindergarten, first grade, and second grade will begin school tomorrow, August 10th. Virtual students in K, 1, and 2 will log in to their Google classrooms on Wednesday, August 12th.

Pre-K, third grade and fourth grade virtual students will begin their classes tomorrow, August 10th. Please see your schedule in your google classroom for your login times.

Students may enter the building at 7:10. The tardy bell rings at 7:40. (If your child is eating breakfast, please make sure they are no later than 7:25.)

Louisiana 4-H
May 28 at 3:00 PM ·

Alright STOP! Collaborate and LISTEN! Camp is BACK in a brand new FORMAT! Yes! You read that correctly!

2 months of VIRTUAL SUMMER CAMP with Grant Walker Educational Center is starting June 8. 4 tracks will be offered over the next two months including: SET (Science, Engineering & Technology), Growth in Gardening, Shoot for the Stars (Photography and Videography), and BBQ Bootcamp (Animal/Meat Science). Lessons are primarily designed for 4-6 graders; however, there will be some lessons that are suitable for 2nd grade all the way to 8th.

Register TODAY: https://bit.ly/LA4-HCamp

P.S. Camp registration is open to ALL youth this year--whether enrolled in 4-H or not and is being offered at ZERO cost, so feel free to share and get the word out!

For questions or concerns, please reach out to Grant Walker's Educational Programs Coordinator, Adam O'Malley via email at AOMalley@agcenter.lsu.edu

See y'all around the campfire real soon! #InspireKidsToDo #Louisiana4H #CloversOnTheBayou #GrantWalkerEducationalCenter #VirtualSummerCamp

post_text: As most of you already know, Governor Edwards officially closed public school facilities for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year. However, learning will continue thru distance education means, as well as paper packets. Each teacher is preparing packets to provide some excellent learning opportunities for the remainder of the school year. Packets will be completed and placed on the front porch of the school on Tuesday, April 21st in filing cabinets. Please come at your convenience and pick up your child's learning packet. If your child has completed the first packet you may drop it off in the bottom drawer of the filing cabinet for their teacher. Remember to follow CDC and Social Distancing guidelines during the pickup. Please share!

Are you looking for something fun to do with your child and have some left over food coloring from Easter? Try SOAP FOAM!

This is a fun sensory play activity that can also be extended to teach math (measuring) and science (senses, color recognition, color mixing) skills.

All you need is dish soap, water, food coloring, a blender and a tray to pour it on!

*reminder* food coloring can stain so be sure to wear old clothes! :)

Is your child having trouble understanding what’s going on and why we are all at home instead of at school and why they aren’t able to hang out with their family and friends like usual?
Check out WHO’s live reading of “My Hero is You, How Kids Can Fight COVID-19” at 10:00am (3:00pmGMT) today on youtube.com/WHO!
shared_text:
World Health Organization (WHO)
April 9 at 12:49 PM ·

Kids, meet Ario - a kind, orange dragon with a horn like a unicorn, who will introduce you to COVID-19 and help you understand how to protect yourself, your families and friends from the coronavirus.

A new story book “My Hero is You, How kids can fight COVID-19!” - aimed at children aged 6-11 years old, is released today to help children understand and come to terms with COVID-19.
The story book also explains to children how to manage difficult emotions when confronted with a new and rapidly changing reality.

This book has been produced by a collaboration of more than 50 organizations working in the humanitarian sector, incl. WHO, UNICEF, UNHCR, the UN Refugee Agency, International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies and Save the Children US.

We are grateful to Howard Donald for giving the first public reading of this book “My Hero is You - how kids can fight COVID-19" in support of the "Read The World" initiative by the International Publishers Association, UNICEF & WHO.

Watch the reading on our YouTube - link in comment below!

Good morning Little Pels and Pel families! Homer Elementary teachers have worked tirelessly to create a distance learning option that will benefit our students during Louisiana’s Stay at Home order.

View each grade level’s page for websites your student(s) can use and each teacher’s page for more directed learning!! You can also “Get Moving” and keep your bodies and minds in tip top shape, and continue with our Character Curriculum that teaches students how to treat others right, make smart choices, and maximize potential! If that’s not enough, go on a virtual field trip to places like the zoo, a cave in Vietnam, Ancient Egypt, museums, and more!

Your teachers are available to support you in any way they can and can be reached via email Monday-Friday from 7:30am-3:00pm! Their email address can be found on the website.

“Never stop learning; for when we stop learning, we stop growing.”

shared_text:
Governor John Bel Edwards
March 13 at 6:07 PM ·

Today, I signed a proclamation that immediately halts any gathering of more than 250 people until Monday, April 13, closes all K-12 public schools statewide effective Monday, March 16 and also moves upcoming state elections.

We are at an inflection point now and we are going to take bold action to minimize the further spread of this illness. That is why I am issuing this order today, ending all events of more than 250 people, closing our schools, and reducing the amount of face-to-face public interaction at state government buildings.

In a separate executive order I will grant Secretary of State Kyle Ardoin’s request to move our upcoming elections for April and May to June and July. The limits on gatherings of 250 people or more statewide is based on federal CDC guidance given the community spread which we are currently experiencing. These steps are necessary to protect the health and safety of the people of Louisiana from the risk of COVID-19.

📰: https://gov.louisiana.gov/index.cfm/newsroom/detail/2403

Claiborne Parish School District
December 12, 2019 at 2:47 PM ·

To all Homer parents and guardians:

As you know, the town of Homer has a leak in the water system causing a shutdown of the town water supply. We have supplied drinking water for all of the Homer schools for the safety and comfort of your children. At this time we are uncertain of when the leak will be repaired. If it is not repaired in a timely fashion we may need to release school and run the busses at about noon today. We wanted to let you know of this possibility in case you need to make arrangements for your child. If you have any questions, please contact your child's school. We will keep you updated when we know more.

Congratulations to our 1st - 4th grade students and teachers for winning the Claiborne Parish ZEARN Competition!! Our students outperformed the other schools (1st-5th grades) in our district by completing the highest percentage of ZEARN lessons per week!!! We even had multiple classrooms complete 100% of their ZEARN lessons every week during the competition. We are so proud of our students and teachers for working so hard and earning us the ZEARN competition winners for the 2nd year in a row!!!

post_text: We had such a special ceremony honoring our local veterans at Homer Elementary School this morning! It was very chilly, but our 4th grade 4H and FFA leaders from Homer High school lead our school in Retiring some American Flags the proper way. They did such a great job. Afterward, they helped serve cake and punch as a special thank you for the veterans time and service! Thank you Homer Elementary school 4H and Homer High School FFA ladies for stepping up and being our future leaders!!
